import java.io.*; // for input/output streams (InputStreams, OutputStream)
// import javax xml parsing library; it'll be InputSource instead of FileInputSOURCE in a real-world scenario: e.g., new SAXParser() or DOMBuilder().   For learning purposes only since we are using builtin classes from java 10+ which is more stable and less error prone compared to external libraries
import javax.xml.*; // for all xml interfaces (Element, Attribute etc.) as well parsing services like the new SAXParser in a real-world scenario: e.g., InputSource instead of FileInputSOURCE 
// import org equivalent classes; it's more error prone and less stable compared to using builtin Java libraries such as XMLDecoder or JAXP (Java API for parsing, validation) etc... But in the case we have not used any external library then that is better.   For learning purposes only since java standard does provide InputSource interface which can read from a stream of data instead FileInputStream/FileReader
import org.xml.sax.*; // SAX parser to parse XML document by reading it one fragment at time  and provides callback mechanism for event driven parsing (like element, attribute etc.) detection in the input source    For learning purposes only since we are using builtin classes from java which is more stable compared with external libraries
import org.w3c.dom.*; // interface to work on XML document object model   Like JDOM or DOMBuilder provided by SAX parser but provides a bit less functionality as it deals directly against Document (not InputSource)  But again, since we have not used any External library then that is better
import javax.security.auth.callback.*; // for security sensitive operations like getting username/password from users etc... this class java_52519_XMLParser_A01 Callback method to provide these details     For learning purposes only because java standard provides methods of SecurityCallback and Authenticator which can be replaced in real world scenarios as per our use case